WEBVTT

00:00.867 --> 00:03.036
               ♪♪               

00:06.039 --> 00:09.175
      [indistinct chatter]      

00:18.618 --> 00:20.653
     - [whispering]: The day    
     my children were taken.    

00:20.687 --> 00:22.389
       The day my children      
           were taken.          

00:22.422 --> 00:23.623
       I'm a good mother.       

00:27.994 --> 00:30.964
  I'm strong. Keep it together. 

00:30.997 --> 00:33.466
     [indistinct whispering]    

00:42.575 --> 00:43.810
       I'm a good mother.       

00:43.843 --> 00:46.046
              I'm a good mother.

00:47.280 --> 00:48.681
                        - Go on.

00:59.592 --> 01:02.295
      - [woman]: All rise.      
    Judge Fleming presiding.    

01:08.301 --> 01:09.502
- Welcome.                      

01:17.811 --> 01:19.412
Counsel.                        

01:20.246 --> 01:22.549
- Thank you, Your Honour.       
Leading up                      

01:22.582 --> 01:25.251
to the removal                  
of the Little Bird children,    

01:25.285 --> 01:27.220
the social workers              
who were present noted          

01:27.253 --> 01:29.055
a number                        
of signs of neglect,            

01:29.089 --> 01:31.157
including                       
inadequate food,                

01:31.191 --> 01:33.159
unfit living conditions,        

01:33.193 --> 01:35.495
                and a sick child
            kept in a crawlspace

01:35.528 --> 01:38.665
       under the floor as a part
     of some type of punishment.

01:39.699 --> 01:41.734
       - [Fleming]: What's      
  the recommendation, Counsel?  

01:41.768 --> 01:44.337
 - [counsel]: My recommendation 
      is that the children      

01:44.370 --> 01:46.639
   who are now in foster care   
          and thriving          

01:46.673 --> 01:49.309
     become permanent wards     
    of the Crown and be given   

01:49.342 --> 01:51.544
  a fair chance of integration  
     into Canadian society.     

01:51.578 --> 01:53.179
          - [Fleming]:          
     Will the representative    

01:53.213 --> 01:55.381
    of the Little Bird family   
          corroborate?          

01:56.149 --> 01:57.817
       - Thank you kindly,      
            Counsel.            

01:57.851 --> 01:59.986
      [clearing her throat]     
          I can confirm         

02:00.019 --> 02:02.689
  that this report is accurate  
            and true            

02:02.722 --> 02:06.192
      and matches my notes      
 on the situation that we found.

02:06.226 --> 02:07.994
       I would like to add      
       that the father is       

02:08.027 --> 02:10.797
            no longer           
         in the picture.        

02:10.830 --> 02:13.166
    The mother is all alone.    

02:13.199 --> 02:15.368
Therefore, I am                 
in full support                 

02:15.401 --> 02:17.537
  of Counsel's recommendation.  
  - [Fleming]: Can you confirm  

02:17.570 --> 02:19.472
 that the children are thriving 
         in foster care?        

02:19.506 --> 02:21.975
- Oh, yes. And there has been   
significant interest            

02:22.008 --> 02:23.877
in all three children           
from very good homes            

02:23.910 --> 02:25.845
who are looking                 
to adopt.                       

02:39.292 --> 02:41.394
  - [Fleming]: This court finds 
 that it's in the best interest 

02:41.427 --> 02:44.364
of the children that they become
  permanent wards of the Crown. 

02:44.397 --> 02:46.733
       Thank you, Counsel.      
        [gavel taps once]       

02:46.766 --> 02:48.635
      - [woman]: All rise!      

02:49.636 --> 02:53.540
   - I... I have this to say.   
          - It's over.          

02:56.142 --> 02:58.378
      [indistinct chatter]      

03:01.281 --> 03:05.118
      [bawling and wailing]     

03:33.479 --> 03:36.249
          [man speaking         
      Indigenous language]      

03:36.282 --> 03:38.518
        ["I remember you"       
   sung by Buffy Sainte-Marie]  

03:38.551 --> 03:42.455
     - ♪ Hey, little bird,      
        I remember you ♪        

03:42.488 --> 03:46.192
    ♪ You with your dreams up   
   higher than you could fly ♪  

03:46.226 --> 03:49.963
     ♪ Hey, I remember you ♪    

03:49.996 --> 03:53.233
    ♪ Hey, hey, little bird ♪   

03:53.266 --> 03:55.635
   ♪ Lost in the summer sun ♪   

03:56.536 --> 03:59.806
      ♪ Those were the days     
  when your feathers were new ♪ 

03:59.839 --> 04:03.076
     ♪ And I remember you ♪     

04:03.109 --> 04:05.345
         ♪ Little bird ♪        

04:05.378 --> 04:07.814
  ♪ Now it's all coming back ♪  

04:08.548 --> 04:11.284
        ♪ The whole world       
        is your habitat ♪       

04:11.317 --> 04:13.019
     ♪ But more than that ♪     

04:13.052 --> 04:16.656
       ♪ If we meet again,      
       will you know me? ♪      

04:16.689 --> 04:19.559
       ♪ So, little bird ♪      

04:19.592 --> 04:23.229
      ♪ Flash your colours      
        and I will sing ♪       

04:23.263 --> 04:26.299
        ♪ Glide into time       
  with the moon on your wing ♪  

04:26.332 --> 04:28.268
         ♪ Little bird ♪        

04:30.036 --> 04:32.272
         ♪ Little bird ♪        

04:33.139 --> 04:35.208
         ♪ Little bird ♪        

04:35.241 --> 04:37.610
   ♪ Like a gull of the sea ♪   

04:39.345 --> 04:42.181
     ♪ Your resting place ♪     

04:42.215 --> 04:44.917
        ♪ Could be heaven       
      or countless oceans ♪     

04:44.951 --> 04:47.320
        ♪ Far from me ♪         

04:56.262 --> 04:57.930
  - Hi, sweetheart. Come here.  

04:57.964 --> 05:00.300
      Give me a hug. Ohhh!      

05:02.468 --> 05:04.304
        How was your day?       
             - Cool.            

05:04.337 --> 05:06.139
         [kid laughing]         

05:06.172 --> 05:08.775
  - [Adele]: Where did you find 
           this ball?           

05:08.808 --> 05:10.109
           Next door?           

05:10.143 --> 05:12.378
  [girl speaking indistinctly]  

05:12.412 --> 05:14.580
       Oh! Who's winning?       

05:15.748 --> 05:17.250
            Oh-ho-ho!           

05:21.754 --> 05:25.425
        [car door slams]        
  [Adele speaking indistinctly] 

05:33.566 --> 05:35.635
 Did you follow me to my house? 

05:36.369 --> 05:38.304
        - Well, I thought       
      that maybe you might      

05:38.338 --> 05:40.139
           talk to me           
    in a less formal setting.   

05:40.173 --> 05:42.275
  - You can't come to my home!  

05:43.042 --> 05:45.611
       - Look, I wouldn't       
        normally do this,       

05:45.645 --> 05:47.480
    but I felt like you were    
    about to say something--    

05:47.513 --> 05:49.549
       - I can't help you.      
            - I know,           

05:49.582 --> 05:52.652
      but I know this isn't     
   how this is supposed to go.  

05:55.121 --> 05:58.825
       But what if your daughter
     never got to meet your son?

05:58.858 --> 06:01.060
          [Adele sighs]         

06:01.094 --> 06:02.795
         I just don't understand
                       what harm

06:02.829 --> 06:05.665
you or child protective services
              think it would do.

06:06.866 --> 06:09.669
      - Come back to the office,
      and I'll check with legal.

06:09.702 --> 06:11.304
   - Legal isn't gonna release  
     any of my information.     

06:11.337 --> 06:13.005
- Look, I need                  
to get lunch on.                

06:13.039 --> 06:15.041
         - Wait. Please.        

06:17.143 --> 06:19.078
            In case you remember
                    something...

06:23.416 --> 06:26.386
   - [whispering]: Do not come  
       to my house again.       

06:30.123 --> 06:31.891
Go inside.                      

06:33.459 --> 06:36.028
          [dog barking]         

06:49.976 --> 06:52.345
        - [girl]: Bezhig?       

06:54.313 --> 06:58.017
       Bezhig, I need you.      
         [child crying]         

06:58.050 --> 07:01.354
  - [Esther]: Do you have sense 
     of where Dora might be?    

07:01.387 --> 07:04.857
  - [woman]: I haven't seen her 
        in five years now.      

07:04.891 --> 07:06.659
           She ran off.         

07:08.694 --> 07:11.063
  - [Esther]: You... you didn't 
     report it to the police?   

07:11.097 --> 07:13.399
         - [young man]:         
  She didn't run away from home.

07:13.433 --> 07:16.035
       She was kicked out.      

07:16.068 --> 07:18.104
        [paper rustling]        

07:20.072 --> 07:21.974
       [thunder growling]       

07:39.091 --> 07:41.627
            [exhales]           

07:47.266 --> 07:49.068
        - Where are you?        

07:49.101 --> 07:50.970
      [train horn blaring]      

07:53.372 --> 07:55.775
      [train horn blaring]      

07:55.808 --> 07:58.110
[train wheels clanking on rails]

08:38.050 --> 08:40.052
        [traffic noises]        

09:31.470 --> 09:33.506
        [exhales slowly]        

09:38.644 --> 09:40.813
        [door squeaking]        
      [second door closes]      

09:40.846 --> 09:43.649
  [traditional Native drumming  
          and chanting]         

09:51.457 --> 09:53.159
        - Ah, you're hurting me!

09:53.192 --> 09:55.661
       - Stop moving then. Geez!

09:55.695 --> 09:58.197
- I love                        
your costume.                   

09:58.230 --> 10:00.566
           - It's not a costume.

10:01.767 --> 10:03.769
    [man greeting in Ojibwe]    

10:03.803 --> 10:05.671
   - I was beginning to think   
  that we were the only Natives 

10:05.705 --> 10:08.474
         at this hotel.         
  Are you here for the pow-wow? 

10:08.507 --> 10:10.443
            - Me? No.           

10:10.476 --> 10:12.912
      I mean, I would have      
        loved to, but...        

10:12.945 --> 10:15.848
      - Where are you from?     
           - Montreal.          

10:15.881 --> 10:18.250
- Hahaha! No,                   
where are you from?             

10:20.252 --> 10:22.521
     - I'm not really sure.     

10:22.555 --> 10:25.291
- Well, say no more.            
I'm Cliff.                      

10:25.324 --> 10:26.692
            - Esther.           

10:26.726 --> 10:30.129
       But also... Bezhig?      

10:30.162 --> 10:31.964
           - Bezhig? Oh, Bezhig?

10:31.998 --> 10:34.066
         That means "number one"
                      in Ojibwe.

10:34.100 --> 10:35.234
- Ojibwe?                       

10:35.267 --> 10:37.069
      Where are they from?      
            - We come           

10:37.103 --> 10:39.205
        from all over the place.
        We spread like wildfire.

10:39.238 --> 10:40.640
    [Cliff and Esther laugh]    

10:40.673 --> 10:43.275
        - [woman]: Cliff!       
  Come help me with these bags! 

10:43.309 --> 10:44.644
 [Native drumming and chanting] 

10:44.677 --> 10:47.113
        - I'm gonna dance       
        for you, Bezhig.        

10:54.220 --> 10:56.722
          [girl crying]         

10:57.590 --> 10:59.158
         [girl coughing]        

11:00.559 --> 11:02.595
         [wind blowing]         

11:11.170 --> 11:13.372
      [indistinct chatter]      

11:14.674 --> 11:17.009
         [phone ringing]        

11:17.043 --> 11:19.779
                - Hi. I'm hoping
                you can help me.

11:19.812 --> 11:22.682
             I'm looking for any
       public document or record

11:22.715 --> 11:24.316
                      to help me
                 find my sister.

11:24.350 --> 11:26.152
          - It's 13.55.         

11:29.822 --> 11:31.957
      [indistinct chatter]      

11:39.398 --> 11:41.667
Esther Rosenblum?               

11:45.438 --> 11:48.174
Here's your girl.               

11:57.717 --> 11:59.752
                    - Excuse me.

12:03.022 --> 12:05.491
     I need any phone number    
           or address           

12:05.524 --> 12:07.860
 associated with these charges. 

12:07.893 --> 12:10.663
- Well, I can't be giving out   
personal information.           

12:10.696 --> 12:12.932
          - Okay, sure.         

12:17.403 --> 12:19.205
       Can you please call      

12:19.238 --> 12:22.975
   any phone number associated  
    with these charges and...   

12:23.008 --> 12:26.278
 just ask my sister if she wants
     me to have her number?     

12:31.951 --> 12:34.320
               - "Officer called
                    to the scene

12:34.353 --> 12:36.188
on an assault charge."          

12:36.222 --> 12:37.990
No phone number.                

12:39.024 --> 12:42.728
"819, Attley Street,            
apartment 108."                 

12:44.363 --> 12:46.832
Be careful,                     
it's a rough area.              

12:47.600 --> 12:49.902
         - I'll be fine.        
             - Sure.            

12:53.139 --> 12:55.307
             [sighs]            

12:57.409 --> 12:59.044
          [dog barking]         

13:22.535 --> 13:24.103
      [vehicle honks twice]     

13:25.538 --> 13:28.107
[distant indistinct hip-hop song
            playing]            

13:33.779 --> 13:35.314
        [car door closes]       

13:35.347 --> 13:37.983
    [indistinct hip-hop song    
         getting louder]        

13:40.753 --> 13:43.355
   [loud hip-hop song playing]  

13:44.757 --> 13:47.059
    [hip-hop song fading out]   

13:54.333 --> 13:56.535
    [a door opens squeakily]    

13:56.569 --> 13:58.404
        [vehicle honking]       

14:04.376 --> 14:06.445
            [honking]           

14:06.478 --> 14:09.148
 [muffled country song playing] 

14:15.654 --> 14:17.389
          [dog barking]         

14:39.979 --> 14:41.614
         - Anybody home?        

14:41.647 --> 14:43.616
      [another door opens]      

14:43.649 --> 14:45.885
           - [woman]:           
    Who are you looking for?    

14:45.918 --> 14:49.154
   - Oh, hi. Uh, Dora Mueller?  

14:50.155 --> 14:51.657
           - Oh, heck.          

14:51.690 --> 14:54.126
You're about two years too late.

14:56.095 --> 14:57.863
   She didn't die or nothing.   

14:57.897 --> 14:59.431
           She moved.           

14:59.465 --> 15:02.301
- Well, do you have any idea    
where she might be?             

15:04.870 --> 15:08.107
    - Why don't you come in.    
        I made some tea.        

15:19.485 --> 15:21.320
Have a seat!                    

15:21.353 --> 15:22.454
             - Sure.            

15:24.423 --> 15:27.593
    [indistinct hymn playing]   

15:32.865 --> 15:34.867
- You like that?                

15:34.900 --> 15:36.902
     - Hmm. It's beautiful.     

15:36.936 --> 15:39.905
- I've had that a long time.    

15:47.546 --> 15:49.648
                    - Thank you.

15:52.885 --> 15:55.220
- And there's                   
my grandkids.                   

16:02.227 --> 16:04.930
You're not                      
from around here, eh?           

16:06.532 --> 16:09.435
               - No. Not really.

16:10.936 --> 16:12.738
         - That's okay.         

16:12.771 --> 16:15.007
                - Oh, thank you.

16:15.040 --> 16:17.643
               My name is Esther
                     by the way.

16:17.676 --> 16:19.411
           - Hmm. Val.          

16:19.445 --> 16:22.348
            - So, you knew Dora?

16:22.381 --> 16:26.452
           [Val sighs]          
  - That depends. Who's asking? 

16:27.820 --> 16:30.956
       - She's my sister.       
            - Really?           

16:30.990 --> 16:32.725
              - Hard to believe,
                         I know.

16:33.392 --> 16:36.028
              I got this address
       from the police actually.

16:36.061 --> 16:38.464
         [Val laughing]         

16:38.497 --> 16:40.466
      - That's no surprise.     

16:41.700 --> 16:43.569
             - Well, do you know
                  what happened?

16:43.602 --> 16:45.838
                  Why the police
                    were called?

16:45.871 --> 16:48.707
   - It's not my place, but...  

16:48.741 --> 16:50.809
       there was this guy.      

16:50.843 --> 16:52.878
       He is a real loser.      

16:52.911 --> 16:54.713
He's jealous.                   

16:54.747 --> 16:56.882
He didn't like                  
her working the street,         

16:56.915 --> 16:59.318
           so he tried          
        to rough her up.        

16:59.351 --> 17:02.588
      So, she beat the crap     
           out of him.          

17:02.621 --> 17:04.056
         [Val laughing]         

17:04.089 --> 17:06.158
She threw his stuff             
out the window.                 

17:06.191 --> 17:09.595
It was hilarious.               
You should have seen it.        

17:09.628 --> 17:10.929
           [chuckling]          

17:10.963 --> 17:13.432
      She didn't take crap      
     from nobody, that girl.    

17:13.465 --> 17:15.067
             - Wow.             

17:16.135 --> 17:19.538
   Well, do you have any idea   
     where I might find her?    

17:19.571 --> 17:20.839
- Oy.                           

17:20.873 --> 17:23.575
       I haven't seen her       
      since she moved out.      

17:24.376 --> 17:27.546
You could try                   
the outreach centre.            

17:27.579 --> 17:29.681
A lot of the girls go there.    

17:29.715 --> 17:31.283
    It's just over on Albert,   

17:31.316 --> 17:33.752
   about 10 blocks from here.   
          - Thank you.          

17:33.786 --> 17:36.822
 I really appreciate your help. 
      - Well, that's good.      

17:36.855 --> 17:39.091
                 - And this tea.

17:39.124 --> 17:43.162
- Oh, my girl,                  
look at that!                   

17:43.929 --> 17:46.532
              Holy!             
             - Haha!            

17:47.266 --> 17:50.869
 - That's bigger than a snowball
     in the bush in winter.     

17:50.903 --> 17:52.204
       [Esther chuckling]       

17:52.237 --> 17:56.442
   Hey, who gave you this one,  
           lucky girl?          

17:56.475 --> 17:57.943
            - His name is David.

17:57.976 --> 17:59.645
            - Aaah...           

17:59.678 --> 18:01.713
           Is he nice?          

18:01.747 --> 18:05.017
             - Yeah.            
    - Oh. Well, that's good.    

18:05.050 --> 18:07.719
    It's always nice to have    
    a sweet guy in your life.   

18:09.054 --> 18:11.657
  [birds and insects chirping]  

18:28.574 --> 18:30.576
       [engine revving up]      

18:34.980 --> 18:37.716
     [country music playing]    

18:41.019 --> 18:44.056
     - ♪ But I found you ♪      

18:44.089 --> 18:47.126
    ♪ When I wasn't looking ♪   

18:47.159 --> 18:50.729
 ♪ I thought I closed my eyes ♪ 

18:50.762 --> 18:53.532
          ♪ For good ♪          

18:53.565 --> 18:56.135
       ♪ But I got lucky ♪      
      [indistinct chatter]      

18:56.168 --> 18:59.037
              - ...seen the look
       on his ugly fucking face.

18:59.071 --> 19:00.939
        [women laughing]        

19:01.707 --> 19:04.576
   - Dana, the nurse is ready   
   for you and Jeannetta now.   

19:06.111 --> 19:10.249
    - ♪ Set my burdens free ♪   

19:11.016 --> 19:12.351
- Can I help you?               

19:12.384 --> 19:16.121
 - ♪ Lay your love down on me ♪ 

19:16.155 --> 19:17.856
- Can I help you?               

19:17.890 --> 19:19.491
                      - Oh! Yes.

19:20.259 --> 19:22.494
                     I'm looking
                  for my sister.

19:22.528 --> 19:24.863
          Dora Mueller.         
         [phone ringing]        

19:24.897 --> 19:28.000
- Oh... These girls             
know her. Hey.                  

19:28.033 --> 19:30.435
         She's looking for Dora.

19:33.939 --> 19:35.641
- She's my sister.              

19:35.674 --> 19:39.077
   - Get the fuck out of town!  
- Didn't know Dora had a sister.

19:39.111 --> 19:41.380
            Oh, my God, you look
                  just like her.

19:42.147 --> 19:43.782
         - You know her?        
       - Are you kidding?       

19:43.815 --> 19:45.150
                 Dora's my girl.

19:45.184 --> 19:47.319
                     - Fuck off,
              she's my girl too.

19:47.352 --> 19:50.789
- Well, do you have any sense   
of where she might be?          

19:50.822 --> 19:53.325
             - She usually comes
         around here on Fridays.

19:53.358 --> 19:56.295
    - That was for her class,   
    but I think that's done.    

19:56.328 --> 19:59.331
- She's getting her GED. I can't
      fucking keep track of her.

19:59.364 --> 20:01.333
         - Wasn't she picking up
      shifts at that weird place

20:01.366 --> 20:03.435
      with the pool tables?     
           - Ronnie's?          

20:03.468 --> 20:05.537
          - No, Eddy's.         
         - Yeah, Eddy's.        

20:05.571 --> 20:07.539
             Not sure if she has
               any more, though.

20:07.573 --> 20:09.308
            It's like two blocks
                       that way.

20:09.341 --> 20:12.611
       [indistinct voices]      
         [child crying]         

20:12.644 --> 20:15.914
              - You okay, honey?
            Are you okay, honey?

20:17.316 --> 20:20.118
                - Yes. Thank you
                  for your help.

20:20.152 --> 20:22.754
      [indistinct chatter]      
          [baby crying]         

20:28.894 --> 20:31.797
 [indistinct folk song playing] 

20:34.366 --> 20:36.235
     - [young Dora]: Bezhig?    

20:39.004 --> 20:39.972
             Bezhig?            

20:40.005 --> 20:42.474
         [Dora coughing]        

20:44.409 --> 20:46.144
  - [young man]: Spare change?  
          [guitar note]         

20:46.178 --> 20:49.114
        [vehicle honking]       

20:49.147 --> 20:50.682
     - Yeah.                    

20:53.318 --> 20:55.187
        [coins clinking]        
      - Thank you, Sister.      

20:57.689 --> 20:59.891
        [vehicle honking]       

21:02.494 --> 21:05.297
    [indistinct country song    
            playing]            

21:05.330 --> 21:08.400
      [indistinct chatter]      

21:28.854 --> 21:30.422
      - What can I get you?     

21:32.090 --> 21:34.493
       - May I get a glass      
      of red wine, please?      

21:34.526 --> 21:36.995
          - Yeah, I think we got
       wine back here somewhere.

21:54.646 --> 21:56.248
                      Thank you.

21:57.249 --> 21:58.950
          - Thank you.          

22:14.499 --> 22:17.436
      [indistinct chatter]      

22:21.373 --> 22:24.476
    [indistinct country song    
            playing]            

22:42.160 --> 22:44.930
                      Excuse me?

22:47.032 --> 22:49.468
           Are you Dora Mueller?

22:49.501 --> 22:51.470
       - What do you want?      

22:53.672 --> 22:56.708
             - I've been looking
                        for you.

22:57.409 --> 22:59.411
   - Well, who the fuck are you?

23:07.185 --> 23:09.321
              - I'm your sister.

23:11.156 --> 23:13.558
                 I went to child
            protective services,

23:13.592 --> 23:15.827
                and they gave me
                      your name.

23:17.329 --> 23:19.564
              They said you were
             looking for family.

23:19.598 --> 23:20.365
- Yeah.                         

23:20.399 --> 23:22.200
           Yeah, yeah.          
          - I'm Bezhig.         

23:22.234 --> 23:26.638
          [both crying]         
     - Holy shit! Holy shit!    

23:29.007 --> 23:30.776
           Oh, my God!          

23:31.743 --> 23:34.479
  This whole time, I was like,  
     "I know I have a sister    

23:34.513 --> 23:36.515
      out there somewhere."     
     I didn't know if I was     

23:36.548 --> 23:39.151
      making it up or what.     

23:39.184 --> 23:41.820
           [sniffling]          

23:44.356 --> 23:46.591
      Where have you been?      

23:46.625 --> 23:49.227
  Where the fuck have you been? 
          [Dora crying]         

23:49.261 --> 23:50.929
Look so fancy.                  

23:50.962 --> 23:52.497
          - You are so pregnant.

23:52.531 --> 23:55.534
- Yes. Yeah, I'm pregnant.      

23:58.770 --> 24:00.672
     Holy fuck!                 

24:00.705 --> 24:02.073
         Hahahaha!              

24:02.107 --> 24:04.276
My sister Bezhig.               

24:04.309 --> 24:06.778
          [Dora crying]         

24:08.613 --> 24:11.283
         [birds singing]        
          [dog barking]         

24:11.316 --> 24:13.919
         [siren blaring]        

24:13.952 --> 24:15.587
This is your car?               

24:15.620 --> 24:17.856
- Well, no, it's a rental.      

24:17.889 --> 24:19.491
- Okay, cool.                   

24:21.126 --> 24:22.828
            - Okay...           

24:27.232 --> 24:28.867
        [car door closes]       

24:30.068 --> 24:32.237
        [car door closes]       

24:32.270 --> 24:35.907
       [seatbelt clicking]      

24:37.676 --> 24:39.544
                So, are you rich
                   or something?

24:39.578 --> 24:40.912
         [Bezhig scoffs]        

24:40.946 --> 24:42.481
- No. Not compared              

24:42.514 --> 24:44.916
to the people                   
who are really rich.            

24:50.355 --> 24:52.824
        You look so good.       
         [Dora chuckles]        

24:52.858 --> 24:55.527
    - Thanks. What did you think
                  I'd look like?

24:55.560 --> 24:58.063
- I mean, I didn't know         
what to think.                  

25:00.532 --> 25:02.467
I had to find you               
through the police,             

25:02.501 --> 25:04.936
and I saw                       
some charges.                   

25:04.970 --> 25:07.439
And I just got worried.         

25:07.472 --> 25:09.341
    - Don't assume shit about me
            just 'cause you read

25:09.374 --> 25:11.943
              some fucking file.
              You don't know me!

25:16.114 --> 25:17.649
- Sorry.                        

25:18.416 --> 25:20.218
I didn't mean                   
to offend you.                  

25:25.857 --> 25:28.527
I'm just really happy           
to find you.                    

25:29.928 --> 25:31.563
That's all.                     

25:33.532 --> 25:35.667
                  - So what now?

25:43.008 --> 25:44.943
- Can we start over?            

25:46.244 --> 25:48.580
I was rude, and...              

25:48.613 --> 25:50.982
I shouldn't have made           
assumptions about you.          

25:51.983 --> 25:55.387
         [Dora laughing]        
 - Do you always talk like that?

25:55.420 --> 25:57.355
               Are you a teacher
                   or something?

25:57.389 --> 25:59.291
- A lawyer.                     

25:59.324 --> 26:01.459
Well, not yet but soon.         

26:01.493 --> 26:03.828
                    - Holy, just
                 a lawyer? Haha!

26:03.862 --> 26:05.196
                   Jesus Christ!

26:05.230 --> 26:07.232
 No wonder you thought I was all
           fucking down-and-out.

26:07.265 --> 26:10.035
                 Hahahaha! Geez.

26:10.068 --> 26:12.404
         I'm just kidding, fuck.

26:12.437 --> 26:14.639
               Do you wanna come
                   to my mansion

26:14.673 --> 26:17.309
                 and meet my man
                     or... what?

26:17.342 --> 26:19.578
          If we stay around here
   much longer, people are gonna

26:19.611 --> 26:21.880
     think we're fucking dealing
                   or some shit.

26:22.681 --> 26:24.883
             - Sure.            
        - Yeah, let's go.       

26:25.884 --> 26:28.553
- You should probably put       
your seatbelt on.               

26:28.587 --> 26:31.156
     - Why, 'cause it's the law?

26:31.189 --> 26:34.025
         [Dora laughing]        

26:34.059 --> 26:36.294
     [country music playing     
           over radio]          

26:47.572 --> 26:50.241
       - ♪ Well, you know       
     I'm not praying from ♪     

26:50.275 --> 26:51.710
               ♪♪               

26:51.743 --> 26:53.612
               - Oh, take a left
                        up here.

26:53.645 --> 26:55.680
             - Okay.            
       [flasher clicking]       

26:55.714 --> 26:57.849
      - ♪ Someone to love ♪     

26:57.882 --> 27:00.251
     ♪ Just a little while ♪    

27:00.285 --> 27:02.153
                 - Anywhere here
                        is fine.

27:02.187 --> 27:05.523
   - ♪ Though those first few   
      months were lovely ♪      

27:05.557 --> 27:07.959
        - So, Eddy seemed       
       like a nice place.       

27:08.660 --> 27:11.763
      - No, it's not. It's      
  fucking gross. But he pays me 

27:11.796 --> 27:14.733
 under the table, so I can still
   collect my welfare cheques.  

27:15.967 --> 27:18.370
         - Okay. Great.         

27:18.403 --> 27:20.271
       [country song ends]      

27:21.673 --> 27:23.975
         [dogs barking]         
      [indistinct speaking]     

27:34.285 --> 27:36.054
- Come in. Over here.           

27:39.391 --> 27:41.192
             - Wow.             

27:41.226 --> 27:44.663
   It's a cute little house...  
    in a nice neighbourhood.    

27:44.696 --> 27:46.164
         [siren blaring]        

27:46.197 --> 27:50.035
    [indistinct song playing]   
       - Baby? Guess what.      

27:51.803 --> 27:53.204
              Hey.              
          - [man]: Hey.         

27:53.238 --> 27:55.774
     What, you're pregnant?     
       - [laughing]: Yeah.      

27:55.807 --> 27:59.210
  - Baby, um, this is my sister.

28:02.247 --> 28:04.349
                          - Wow!

28:04.382 --> 28:06.718
            Shit! Oh!           
            - Hahaha!           

28:06.751 --> 28:09.320
- Okay. Uh...                   
I'm Doug.                       

28:09.354 --> 28:12.624
            - Esther.           
       - Good to meet you.      

28:13.358 --> 28:15.026
                          - Wow!

28:15.060 --> 28:16.528
               I don't even know
              what to say. Uh...

28:16.561 --> 28:18.596
            - I know.           
           [chuckling]          

28:18.630 --> 28:20.131
- Well, Sister, uh,             

28:20.165 --> 28:22.467
come have a seat.               
Can I take your jacket?         

28:22.500 --> 28:24.569
        - Oh, yeah, sure.       

28:24.602 --> 28:27.205
           Thank you.           
       - Yeah, no problem.      

28:28.206 --> 28:30.175
          - Thank you.          
             - Uh...            

28:31.042 --> 28:33.645
    Baby, you need anything?    
   - Uh, just a water, please.  

28:33.678 --> 28:35.346
             - Okay.            
          - Thank you.          

28:36.314 --> 28:38.616
         [Dora exhales]         

28:38.650 --> 28:42.287
            So, I put my name in
  the child protective services,

28:42.320 --> 28:44.989
                       like, um,
                 four years ago,

28:45.023 --> 28:47.525
            you know, for family
                      and, um...

28:47.559 --> 28:49.861
                   I wasn't even
                looking looking.

28:49.894 --> 28:52.897
             Um... I just needed
                a place to stay.

28:54.065 --> 28:56.801
          Here she is.          
   - Yeah, you ordered her up.  

28:56.835 --> 28:59.237
             - Yeah.            
        [Dora chuckling]        

28:59.270 --> 29:00.672
Hoho! Oh, man,                  

29:00.705 --> 29:02.173
even baby thought               
that was funny.                 

29:02.207 --> 29:05.276
             - Haha!            
   - She's doing somersaults.   

29:05.310 --> 29:07.412
      [Dora exhales slowly]     

29:07.445 --> 29:09.013
Feel.                           

29:10.749 --> 29:11.850
    [Dora clears her throat]    

29:11.883 --> 29:14.152
 - ♪ There's a million wishing ♪

29:14.185 --> 29:18.289
               - Baby girl, it's
            your auntie, Bezhig.

29:18.323 --> 29:20.158
                         Hahaha!

29:21.392 --> 29:22.360
         [Dora sniffles]        

29:22.393 --> 29:24.362
      - ♪ Just let it go ♪      

29:24.395 --> 29:26.397
                 - Man, I didn't
                      even think

29:26.431 --> 29:28.233
            this baby would have
                    any aunties.

29:30.401 --> 29:32.704
   - I met your adoptive family.

29:34.272 --> 29:35.874
                         - What?

29:36.775 --> 29:39.444
         - Well, it was         
     one of the first places    

29:39.477 --> 29:41.913
      I went to, you know,      
        try to find you.        

29:42.714 --> 29:46.151
Your mom seemed cold,           
but your brother seemed nice.   

29:47.485 --> 29:48.853
             - Fuck them.       

29:49.621 --> 29:51.189
     - Yeah, I got the sense    

29:51.222 --> 29:53.591
    it didn't really go well    
           with them.           

29:53.625 --> 29:55.527
            - It doesn't matter.

29:56.327 --> 29:59.864
        They didn't win.        
   [Dora takes a deep breath]   

30:03.168 --> 30:04.235
        - Seems like Dora       

30:04.269 --> 30:07.238
        hit the jackpot with you
            for an older sister.

30:07.272 --> 30:09.440
     Maybe you becoming a lawyer
                   and all that.

30:10.775 --> 30:12.410
                  - I don't know
                     about that.

30:14.312 --> 30:16.447
                    - This girl,

30:16.481 --> 30:18.316
      let me tell you something,

30:18.349 --> 30:20.118
        you hit the jackpot too.

30:20.151 --> 30:22.253
        - Come on, stop.        

30:22.287 --> 30:24.823
              - For real though.
              The way you pulled

30:24.856 --> 30:27.192
       yourself up, like getting
          your GED and all that.

30:29.093 --> 30:31.596
      Hope it's okay to say, but
   when I first met her, she was

30:31.629 --> 30:33.898
 this scrappy little angry ball.

30:33.932 --> 30:37.035
           [chuckling]          
      Now you put your hand     

30:37.068 --> 30:39.370
        on her shoulder,        
  she'd jump like a stray cat.  

30:41.606 --> 30:43.408
She's been                      
through a lot.                  

30:45.009 --> 30:46.744
         But there ain't nothing
               keeping her down,

30:46.778 --> 30:48.346
          ain't that right, Mom?

30:55.220 --> 30:57.789
       - I'm sorry you had to go
               through all that.

31:00.825 --> 31:03.361
          - It made me stronger.

31:09.400 --> 31:11.569
- Working my way up             
to own my own restaurant        

31:11.603 --> 31:14.172
  and working shifts for whoever
    will put me on the schedule,

31:14.205 --> 31:15.940
                       you know.

31:15.974 --> 31:18.142
         It's tough pulling gigs
          when you got a record.

31:19.143 --> 31:20.945
          - Yeah, well,         
      you're a great cook,      

31:20.979 --> 31:23.548
         so I don't see         
     why it won't work out.     

31:26.985 --> 31:28.686
          - Getting tired, Mama?

31:28.720 --> 31:30.154
             - Yeah.            

31:31.589 --> 31:34.158
         - I am so happy        
          that we met.          

31:35.660 --> 31:37.962
        I've been staring       

31:37.996 --> 31:39.898
         at these photos        
    that your brother gave me   

